1NT pass 3NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "41bc0b33a9964239af760faececb1b76d9f3f05f72c93346c06687fd15fe57c4"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/holdup_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{With his 4-3-3-3 distribution West chooses not to bother with Stayman. East is to play 3NT. South leads the \H6. North plays the \HJ.

Winners:   \S=1  \H=1  \D=3  \C=2  Total = 7

You need to get two more winners. The \H suit might provide one of them, but you will still have to establish \Ss. The burning question is whether to win the first \H or to hold up. If you take this trick you will have a second stopper if South takes the lead, but you will be in extreme danger if North takes the lead. Since the \S finesse has to go into North you should hold up.

North returns the \H9, South takes the \HA and clears the suit.

You have lost two tricks so far. Lead the \SJ and let it ride. North wins their third trick with the \SK but has no \H to return so he plays a \D which you win with your \DA.

Play off your 7 winners and give up a \C at the end.

The  K Q x holding is similar to the A J x holding. It might be two stoppers, or might just be one, depending on which defender next leads the suit.

So you decide whether to hold up or not based on how you expect to play the hand.}
[Play "W"]H6

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
